WEBVTT

00:03.920 --> 00:04.960
Meredith: Adrenaline
is the body's response

00:04.960 --> 00:06.210
to stressful situations.

00:06.210 --> 00:07.710
Hey. Wait, wai-- wait.

00:07.710 --> 00:11.580
I proofread the presentation,
tested the A/V equipment.

00:11.580 --> 00:13.040
David Bowie
is performance-ready.

00:13.040 --> 00:14.210
Excellent.

00:14.210 --> 00:15.330
Where are you going?

00:15.330 --> 00:16.790
I'm going to check
on my post-ops.

00:16.790 --> 00:18.170
I'll be back soon.
What?

00:18.170 --> 00:20.540
Try to calm down.
You're gonna stress out Bowie.

00:20.540 --> 00:23.120
♪ You live your life
out loud ♪

00:23.120 --> 00:24.750
♪ I can see you got
the fever ♪

00:24.750 --> 00:27.620
It's one of many biochemical
compounds our bodies produce

00:27.620 --> 00:29.830
that alter our state
of consciousness.
Hey.

00:29.830 --> 00:31.000
How long
is this gonna take?

00:31.000 --> 00:32.210
Well, it's gonna take
as long as it's gonna take.

00:32.210 --> 00:33.540
We have 25 proposals.

00:33.540 --> 00:34.750
♪ Get up, if y'all
are just sitting around ♪

00:34.750 --> 00:36.830
This eliminates
the need for a port.

00:36.830 --> 00:37.920
That allows us to --

00:37.920 --> 00:39.540
-Hey.
-No. No.

00:39.540 --> 00:41.040
Go away.
Why?

00:41.040 --> 00:42.710
I already lost sleep
because of you last night.
Did you?

00:42.710 --> 00:44.080
-I'm trying to focus.
-Uh-huh.

00:44.080 --> 00:45.880
-I'm trying to win.
-Yeah? Good luck with that.

00:45.880 --> 00:48.620
Oxytocin makes us feel
bonded with others.

00:48.620 --> 00:50.750
I'm going backstage.

00:50.750 --> 00:52.670
Kepner said I could be
the first to present.

00:52.670 --> 00:54.120
Then I'll head
to Ollie's funeral.

00:54.120 --> 00:55.750
Oh, I wish
I could come with you.

00:55.750 --> 00:57.040
It'll be all right.

00:57.040 --> 00:59.000
♪ Oh, oh, oh ♪

00:59.000 --> 01:00.790
Dopamine makes us more alert

01:00.790 --> 01:03.210
and motivates us
to seek reward.

01:03.210 --> 01:06.000
Baby.
Move this box down there.

01:06.000 --> 01:07.330
Mom, if you wanted input,
you could have done that

01:07.330 --> 01:08.710
last week
instead of being in Boston.

01:08.710 --> 01:10.670
I was busy taking care
of business.

01:10.670 --> 01:11.710
So was Dr. Velez.

01:11.710 --> 01:13.000
She had emergency surgery
in L.A.

01:13.000 --> 01:15.330
She still managed
to get her notes in on time.

01:15.330 --> 01:17.000
-Over there.
-[ Clears throat ] Thank you.

01:17.000 --> 01:18.380
That's nasty.

01:18.380 --> 01:20.880
-Hi. Cookie?
-Oh.

01:20.880 --> 01:22.500
Whoa. Seriously?

01:22.500 --> 01:25.380
My girlfriend
just got deported.
Here.

01:25.380 --> 01:28.380
A lack of serotonin
has been linked to depression.

01:28.380 --> 01:29.880
You had time
to make cookies?

01:29.880 --> 01:32.750
They are lesbian
gratitude cookies.

01:32.750 --> 01:33.830
-What?
-Hm. Yeah.

01:33.830 --> 01:34.920
I mean,
that's what they call them.

01:34.920 --> 01:36.330
Remember my patients
who had the cancer

01:36.330 --> 01:37.670
that turned out
not to be cancer?
[ Cellphone chimes ]

01:37.670 --> 01:40.330
Mmm. Lesbian gratitude cookies
are delicious.

01:40.330 --> 01:41.920
I think I can say that,
but I'm not so sure about you.

01:41.920 --> 01:43.250
-Hi. Cookie?
-Hi.

01:43.250 --> 01:45.960
Um, one of my patients
just went into labor.

01:45.960 --> 01:49.420
If I don't make it back,
you got this. You're magic.

01:49.420 --> 01:51.880
GABA, an amino-acid
neurotransmitter,

01:51.880 --> 01:54.170
helps reduce anxiety...

01:54.170 --> 01:55.790
Ooh. Cookie?

01:55.790 --> 01:57.170
♪ 'Cause I'm good to know ♪

01:57.170 --> 01:59.380
Don't mind if I do.

01:59.380 --> 02:00.880
Hmm.

02:00.880 --> 02:02.040
♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

02:02.040 --> 02:04.080
♪ Come along with me money ♪

02:04.080 --> 02:05.500
♪ 'Cause you don't want
to miss the show ♪

02:05.500 --> 02:06.790
And endorphins create

02:06.790 --> 02:08.380
a heightened state
of happiness.

02:08.380 --> 02:09.920
What?
What are you doing here?

02:09.920 --> 02:11.250
You're supposed
to be rounding.

02:11.250 --> 02:12.620
The future of medicine
is in this room.

02:12.620 --> 02:14.960
And that's why the grownups
get first dibs on the seats.

02:14.960 --> 02:17.620
Here. Come on, let's go.
I'm going, too.

02:17.620 --> 02:19.920
Hey, cookie?
Um, no, I can't eat
when I'm nervous.

02:19.920 --> 02:21.500
-I'll throw up, but thank you.
-Hm.

02:21.500 --> 02:23.670
...like the kind
we feel when we win.

02:23.670 --> 02:25.920
April:
Morning and welcome

02:25.920 --> 02:29.830
to Grey Sloan Surgical
Innovation Prototypes Day.

02:29.830 --> 02:33.710
Today, we will see presentations
of the 25 proposals

02:33.710 --> 02:35.710
that were chosen
in round one.

02:35.710 --> 02:39.620
Five will be selected to move on
to the contest's final phase

02:39.620 --> 02:42.670
and receive a $1 million grant

02:42.670 --> 02:45.670
to further their
groundbreaking research.

02:45.670 --> 02:47.420
Good luck to all
of today's presenters.

02:47.420 --> 02:50.920
And we will begin
with Dr. Richard Webber.

02:50.920 --> 02:53.120
[ Cheers and applause ]

02:53.120 --> 02:55.960
[ Applause continues ]

02:55.960 --> 02:56.960
You're on deck.

02:56.960 --> 02:58.500
Hey. Want some cookies?

02:58.500 --> 03:01.880
Sure. Thanks.

03:01.880 --> 03:03.880
Richard: Thank you.

03:03.880 --> 03:07.080
Let's begin.
[ Crunches ]

03:07.080 --> 03:08.790
Now, once we identify
the cancer,

03:08.790 --> 03:09.960
we do everything we can...

03:09.960 --> 03:11.210
You knew we had
to present today.

03:11.210 --> 03:12.420
We had
a very clear deadline.

03:12.420 --> 03:13.960
Yeah, well, cleaning up
the mess you made

03:13.960 --> 03:15.750
has no clear end at all.

03:15.750 --> 03:17.210
[ Sighs ] What mess?
What are you talking about?

03:17.210 --> 03:18.750
The mess you made when you
decided to waive

03:18.750 --> 03:21.080
Rebecca Froy's settlement
against your grandfather,

03:21.080 --> 03:23.380
thereby allowing her
to speak publicly about it,

03:23.380 --> 03:25.500
which sent our foundation's
board of directors

03:25.500 --> 03:27.750
into a massive soaking
of their collective britches,

03:27.750 --> 03:30.000
which I had to sop up.
That mess.

03:30.000 --> 03:32.290
What settlement
are you talking about?

03:32.290 --> 03:33.790
Sexual harassment.

03:33.790 --> 03:35.290
To revolutionize
the way that...

03:35.290 --> 03:37.750
Close your mouth
before you catch a fly.

03:37.750 --> 03:39.120
Dr. Orr!
[ Chuckles ]

03:39.120 --> 03:40.500
[ Softly ]
We'll talk later.

03:40.500 --> 03:44.290
Dr. Orr [Chuckling]
so nice to see you, darling.

03:44.290 --> 03:50.000
So, when you apply
the Path Pen to tissue,

03:50.000 --> 03:52.330
it rapidly identifies

03:52.330 --> 03:56.540
whether a cell is healthy...
[ Chimes ]

03:56.540 --> 03:59.000
...or cancerous.
[ Buzzer ]

03:59.000 --> 04:00.380
So you're showing us
a mock-up?

04:00.380 --> 04:01.960
No, no. It's functional.

04:01.960 --> 04:03.790
I mean, it's still
in the testing stage,

04:03.790 --> 04:05.380
but, at this point,

04:05.380 --> 04:07.920
approximately 80%
of all tumor types we sampled

04:07.920 --> 04:09.330
are in the database,

04:09.330 --> 04:12.170
and we hope for 100%
in the next few months.

04:12.170 --> 04:14.460
Wow. That is impressive.
The Pen uses a...

04:14.460 --> 04:17.380
Impressive? It's like
a drug-sniffing dog for cancer.

04:17.380 --> 04:19.580
-We're screwed.
-Shh! Our idea's good, too.

04:19.580 --> 04:21.080
[ Pager vibrating ]
...mass spectrometer,

04:21.080 --> 04:23.210
which compares biomarkers
from the tissue

04:23.210 --> 04:25.000
with those of the cancer cells
in the database.

04:25.000 --> 04:26.210
The device --

04:26.210 --> 04:28.290
[ Elevator bell dings ]
Hey, Peggy, Dayna.

04:28.290 --> 04:29.790
What's going on? Are you okay?
Is -- Is the baby okay?

04:29.790 --> 04:31.040
No, no, no, we're fine.
Rose is fine.

04:31.040 --> 04:33.080
It's the cookies.

04:33.080 --> 04:34.380
I'm sorry?
You paged me 911.

04:34.380 --> 04:35.880
-We're so sorry.
-We need the cookies back.

04:35.880 --> 04:37.580
-We're so sorry.
-It was an accident.

04:37.580 --> 04:39.040
Do you still have them? Please
say that you still have them.

04:39.040 --> 04:40.670
The cookies?
All of the cookies?

04:40.670 --> 04:42.670
[ Muttering ] All the cookies,
all of the cookies.

04:42.670 --> 04:45.250
Jackson: Current procedures use
a portion of the small intestine

04:45.250 --> 04:47.750
to provide
the feel of the vagina,

04:47.750 --> 04:50.210
but the result can still have
some practical limitations,

04:50.210 --> 04:51.790
due to its ability
to secrete fluid --

04:51.790 --> 04:53.420
peritoneal tissue
is a good choice

04:53.420 --> 04:55.670
for vaginal reconstruction...
[ Whispering ] Hi. Um.

04:55.670 --> 04:57.170
Now let's look at slides.
Could you, um --

04:57.170 --> 04:58.750
do you see
that cookie tin up there?

04:58.750 --> 05:00.120
C-Could you go
get those cookies for me?

05:00.120 --> 05:03.540
I'm a little, uh, wobbly.
I can't.

05:03.540 --> 05:06.040
I'm not going up there.

05:06.040 --> 05:09.880
Go eat the cafeteria cookies
from the green room.
[ Chuckles ]

05:09.880 --> 05:11.170
Okay. [ Clears throat ]

05:11.170 --> 05:13.540
Come here.

05:13.540 --> 05:17.080
My patient accidentally
used peanut-butter cannabis

05:17.080 --> 05:19.540
that her wife had got her when
she was going through chemo.

05:19.540 --> 05:22.170
One thing led to another,
and, um, I seem to have given

05:22.170 --> 05:24.500
a lot of people
weed cookies,

05:24.500 --> 05:26.620
um, with an unknown
and immeasurable amount

05:26.620 --> 05:27.830
of weed in them.

05:27.830 --> 05:29.500
♪♪

05:29.500 --> 05:32.080
Jackson:
The peritoneum naturally
regenerates within days.

05:32.080 --> 05:35.000
She came to us
with the idea...

05:35.000 --> 05:37.250
Who had the cookies?

05:37.250 --> 05:38.790
Who didn't?

05:38.790 --> 05:40.540
Jackson: And that's
when I told them, uh, you know,

05:40.540 --> 05:43.880
I said, "Hey. We can make
a better vagina, you know?"

05:43.880 --> 05:45.250
I'm gonna go back.

05:45.250 --> 05:47.420
That sounds, uh --
That sounds wrong.

05:47.420 --> 05:50.670
Vaginas are terrific
the way they are, honestly.

05:50.670 --> 05:52.250
I love 'em, you know.

05:52.250 --> 05:54.670
Um, I came from one, so...

05:54.670 --> 05:57.330
This one, hers, actually.
[ Chuckles ] Hey, Ma.

05:57.330 --> 05:59.040
That's not
what the script says.

05:59.040 --> 06:00.830
What do we do?
What do we do?

06:00.830 --> 06:03.620
April: [ Giggling ]
What?

06:03.620 --> 06:04.830
Oh, my God.

06:04.830 --> 06:06.080
[ Laughing ] This one.

06:06.080 --> 06:07.620
[ Giggling ]
[ Audience murmuring ]

06:07.620 --> 06:10.040
[ Crunches ]

06:10.040 --> 06:11.460
This is bad.

06:11.460 --> 06:12.790
[ Giggling ]

06:24.540 --> 06:25.580
Due to unforeseen circumstances,
we are postponing

06:25.580 --> 06:27.040
the remainder
of today's presentation.

06:27.040 --> 06:28.420
Please raise your hand

06:28.420 --> 06:31.170
if you ate
any cookies from this tin.

06:31.170 --> 06:34.540
♪♪

06:34.540 --> 06:37.080
Oh.

06:37.080 --> 06:38.670
Unfortunately,
the cookies in this tin

06:38.670 --> 06:40.580
were tainted
with rat poison.

06:40.580 --> 06:42.120
[ Audience gasping ]

06:42.120 --> 06:46.170
So we need to treat those of you
who have ingested them

06:46.170 --> 06:48.580
as soon as possible,
please.

06:48.580 --> 06:50.420
[ Chair creaks ]

06:50.420 --> 06:53.080
♪♪

06:53.080 --> 06:55.210
Okay. False alarm.

06:55.210 --> 06:56.580
The cookies
had marijuana in them.

06:56.580 --> 06:58.040
What?!

06:58.040 --> 06:59.460
Yes.
I didn't want to scare you.

06:59.460 --> 07:00.710
So you went
with rat poison?

07:00.710 --> 07:02.170
You scared me to death.

07:02.170 --> 07:04.080
-What?
-You knew they had weed in them.

07:04.080 --> 07:06.620
Right. Yeah. I-I forgot.
[ Chuckles ]

07:06.620 --> 07:08.210
Okay, so listen.

07:08.210 --> 07:10.210
No one goes anywhere
until you're sober.

07:10.210 --> 07:13.000
Ingesting marijuana
has a much stronger effect,

07:13.000 --> 07:15.880
and it lasts much longer
than when you smoke it, so --

07:15.880 --> 07:18.500
True story. We get kids
in the ER all the time --

07:18.500 --> 07:19.620
They had -- had --
They like the cookies

07:19.620 --> 07:21.040
and the brownies
and the candies.

07:21.040 --> 07:22.540
They should really label
that stuff better.

07:22.540 --> 07:24.960
So everyone stays here.

07:24.960 --> 07:29.380
There's no medicine, no surgery,
and no patient interaction.

07:29.380 --> 07:31.210
Yeah, I -- Yeah, I'm just
gonna send some orders.

07:31.210 --> 07:32.960
No, you're not
gonna send anything!

07:32.960 --> 07:35.080
-Give your note to Jo.
-Wait. You're taking our phones?

07:35.080 --> 07:36.710
Everyone,
give your phones to Wilson.

07:36.710 --> 07:39.000
She will handle your patients,
your post-ops, and your charts.

07:39.000 --> 07:40.210
So you're gonna do
all of our work?

07:40.210 --> 07:41.170
Yes, she's gonna reassess
and rearrange.

07:41.170 --> 07:43.170
-Yeah. Yeah.
-It's gonna be great.

07:43.170 --> 07:45.330
You're so pretty.
You look like a cartoon.
[ Indistinct conversations ]

07:45.330 --> 07:46.710
-Okay, okay.
-You should look into it.

07:46.710 --> 07:48.290
-Phones now.
-Jackson.

07:48.290 --> 07:49.830
Everybody stay here.

07:49.830 --> 07:50.830
-[ Sighs ]
-Right.

07:50.830 --> 07:53.210
-Let's go.
-Oh, my God.

07:53.210 --> 07:55.420
Arizona: Andrew?
[ Door closes ]

07:55.420 --> 07:57.540
Andrew, you in there?

07:57.540 --> 07:58.920
-Andrew?
-Who are we talking about?

07:58.920 --> 08:00.750
Hey, Andrew?
[ Door opens ]

08:00.750 --> 08:03.380
Pierce? Oh, God, Pi--
Andrew. Pi-- Pierce!

08:03.380 --> 08:07.540
Pierce? Hey, Pierce.
Stop. Stop!

08:07.540 --> 08:09.500
Hey.
Owen: [ Breathes sharply ]
They called.

08:09.500 --> 08:11.080
They called, and they said
that he's coming today.

08:11.080 --> 08:12.710
I'm not ready.
-Wait.

08:12.710 --> 08:13.880
Wait up.
Who called?

08:13.880 --> 08:16.210
DSHS. They're bringing me
a foster kid.

08:16.210 --> 08:17.250
-Today?
-Yeah.

08:17.250 --> 08:18.500
I just had
the home inspection,

08:18.500 --> 08:19.710
and they said,
"We'll call you."

08:19.710 --> 08:20.790
I didn't think it would
be this soon,

08:20.790 --> 08:22.460
and now they're bringing me
a baby boy.

08:22.460 --> 08:26.000
I said I could take
ages zero to 17,

08:26.000 --> 08:27.500
and they're
bringing me zero.

08:27.500 --> 08:28.710
Well,
that's amazing, right?

08:28.710 --> 08:30.620
I just got off
a 36-hour shift,

08:30.620 --> 08:33.460
and I came home to sleep,
and I -- I don't have anything.

08:33.460 --> 08:34.620
You're gonna be fine.

08:34.620 --> 08:35.710
Do you need me
to come over and help?

08:35.710 --> 08:37.290
No, no. No, no, no, no.

08:37.290 --> 08:39.170
It's -- T-This
is what I wanted, and...

08:39.170 --> 08:40.920
How soon
can you get here?

08:40.920 --> 08:42.790
I'll be right over.
Woman: Dr. Schwartz to the ER.
Dr. Schwartz to the ER.

08:42.790 --> 08:44.710
Hey. Hi.
Have you seen Pierce?

08:44.710 --> 08:47.380
No. What's with him?

08:47.380 --> 08:49.170
A patient brought in
accidental weed cookies.

08:49.170 --> 08:50.830
[ Whispering ]
And he ate a lot of them.

08:50.830 --> 08:52.290
And Pierce ate one, too.

08:52.290 --> 08:53.420
Oh, my God.
Yeah, I will help you look.

08:53.420 --> 08:55.290
Let me, uh, call Owen
and let him know

08:55.290 --> 08:56.460
I will be there
as soon as I can.

08:56.460 --> 08:57.960
Is Owen okay?

08:57.960 --> 09:00.170
Yeah. He, uh -- He's getting
a foster kid today.

09:00.170 --> 09:01.330
[ Telephone rings ]

09:01.330 --> 09:04.580
Pierce. Pierce. Hey. Stop.

09:04.580 --> 09:06.880
I -- You -- You go.
I got this.

09:06.880 --> 09:09.080
-You got this.
-Stop! Let's go.

09:09.080 --> 09:11.170
Oh, come along.
Hey, we got to go.

09:11.170 --> 09:12.210
Come on.

09:12.210 --> 09:13.580
[ Whispering ]
Come on. Got to go.

09:13.580 --> 09:15.500
Hey, come on.

09:15.500 --> 09:17.000
Hey, Pierce!
[ Clears throat ]

09:17.000 --> 09:18.540
You're supposed
to be in the theater.

09:18.540 --> 09:20.380
[ Whispering ]
I ate marijuana.

09:20.380 --> 09:22.120
I know.

09:22.120 --> 09:23.460
I never
had marijuana before.

09:23.460 --> 09:25.120
Oh, that's -- Really?

09:25.120 --> 09:27.580
I've been drunk before,
and...I-I make poor choices.

09:27.580 --> 09:28.960
Really embarrassing choices
when I'm drunk.

09:28.960 --> 09:30.830
-So I just need to be alone.
-No. No, no, no, no.

09:30.830 --> 09:32.080
You have never
been high before.

09:32.080 --> 09:33.830
You need to be
with people who --

09:33.830 --> 09:37.000
who can help you
and keep you safe.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.170
I don't --

09:38.170 --> 09:41.420
I don't think
I need my neck anymore.

09:41.420 --> 09:42.620
Okay, just --
Here. Come here.

09:42.620 --> 09:44.790
Just go in here.

09:44.790 --> 09:46.880
Oh, my God.

09:46.880 --> 09:48.540
Can you come on?

09:48.540 --> 09:51.710
♪♪

09:51.710 --> 09:54.620
Woman: Dr. Edell to the NICU.
Dr. Edell to the NICU.

09:54.620 --> 09:56.710
Alex?
I figured out how to make
the ultrasound work.

09:56.710 --> 09:59.540
[ Clatters lightly ]
It needs more water.
A waterfall.

09:59.540 --> 10:02.000
Uh, hold up,
Dr. Frankenstein.

10:02.000 --> 10:03.620
Did you eat cookies
this morning?

10:03.620 --> 10:06.670
Oh, yeah. It was so good.
Are there more cookies?

10:06.670 --> 10:07.960
Or, uh, chips?

10:07.960 --> 10:09.120
-Okay.
-You got chips?

10:09.120 --> 10:11.620
You're just coming with me.
[ Groans ]

10:11.620 --> 10:14.210
Okay, but why didn't you
say anything?

10:14.210 --> 10:16.830
Mnh. Turns out there's
no good time to tell your son

10:16.830 --> 10:19.420
that his grandfather
is a sexual predator.

10:19.420 --> 10:21.040
He isn't. He was.

10:21.040 --> 10:24.250
So -- So the accusations
are accurate from Rebecca Frog?

10:24.250 --> 10:25.420
Uh, Frond?

10:25.420 --> 10:27.040
-Froy, Froy.
-Froy.

10:27.040 --> 10:29.460
No, that's not right.
It was like a...

10:29.460 --> 10:31.040
Rebecca Froy's story
was true.

10:31.040 --> 10:32.960
All the stories
were true.

10:32.960 --> 10:34.500
Wait.
What do you mean "all"?

10:34.500 --> 10:36.170
You said "all."
"All the stories"? What's that?

10:36.170 --> 10:39.170
There was many stories --
some ugly, some very ugly.

10:39.170 --> 10:40.500
How many?
How many stories?

10:40.500 --> 10:43.380
13. 13 women --
all under NDAs...
13?

10:43.380 --> 10:44.880
...all secret!

10:44.880 --> 10:46.120
Shh!

10:46.120 --> 10:48.420
This is bad.
This is so bad.

10:48.420 --> 10:52.170
This is indispensable --
fensible -- indefensible.

10:52.170 --> 10:53.170
What are you looking for?

10:53.170 --> 10:54.790
My glasses!

10:55.580 --> 10:57.670
♪♪

10:57.670 --> 10:59.460
Oh. [ Chuckles ]

10:59.460 --> 11:00.500
13, Mom?

11:00.500 --> 11:02.040
13.

11:02.040 --> 11:03.420
Jo: Some attendings

11:03.420 --> 11:05.960
have unexpectedly become...
unavailable.

11:05.960 --> 11:07.500
You will be taking over
their services --

11:07.500 --> 11:09.790
rounding, charting,
whatever needs to get done.

11:09.790 --> 11:11.330
This is a chance
for you to step up.

11:11.330 --> 11:13.080
Isn't that
what we normally do?

11:13.080 --> 11:15.080
It is the same,
but, also, more.

11:15.080 --> 11:16.790
This is a contest.

11:16.790 --> 11:18.500
So keep track
of everything you do,

11:18.500 --> 11:20.710
and whoever accomplishes
the most by the end of the day

11:20.710 --> 11:22.210
gets to scrub in with me
on a whipple.

11:22.210 --> 11:23.790
-Me! I want to do that.
-Yes. Yes, please.

11:23.790 --> 11:24.880
-Okay. Go.
-Go.

11:24.880 --> 11:26.500
-Okay.
-Oh, wait. Hold on.

11:26.500 --> 11:28.380
Did anyone eat cookies
this morning?

11:28.380 --> 11:30.920
A patient brought in cookies
that had rat poison in them.

11:30.920 --> 11:32.750
They were weed cookies,
accidental weed cookies.

11:32.750 --> 11:33.960
They were in a floral tin.
Did anyone eat them?

11:33.960 --> 11:34.960
-No.
-No.

11:34.960 --> 11:36.330
-No.
-Nope.

11:36.330 --> 11:38.040
-Okay. Get to work.
-Okay. Now go.

11:38.040 --> 11:39.540
[ Pager vibrating ]
Uh, yes.

11:39.540 --> 11:41.670
[ Sighing ] Okay.
Bailey's paging me a 911
from the OR.

11:41.670 --> 11:43.880
I got to go.

11:43.880 --> 11:47.080
♪♪

11:47.080 --> 11:52.540
♪♪

11:52.540 --> 11:54.120
Dr. Bailey.

11:54.120 --> 11:59.380
Grey. I'm feeling dizzy
and light-headed and --

11:59.380 --> 12:00.420
I think something's
wrong with her.

12:00.420 --> 12:02.710
I think I know what it is.
Can we page Jo Wilson?

12:02.710 --> 12:06.500
♪♪

12:06.500 --> 12:09.120
I thought it was my heart.

12:09.120 --> 12:11.040
No, this is your brain
on drugs.

12:11.040 --> 12:12.380
[ Scoffs ]
Wait. All of them?

12:12.380 --> 12:14.620
All of my attendings
had a cookie, Grey?

12:14.620 --> 12:16.330
No, just a few and you.

12:16.330 --> 12:18.290
Oh, this is bad.

12:18.290 --> 12:20.460
This is very, very bad.

12:20.460 --> 12:22.250
I opened that man up.

12:22.250 --> 12:23.920
I'm into his peritoneum.

12:23.920 --> 12:25.580
I'm into him.

12:25.580 --> 12:29.120
Dr. Bailey, it's okay.
I'm here.

12:29.120 --> 12:30.790
I'm going to finish this
for you.

12:30.790 --> 12:32.210
-Total gastrectomy.
-Mm.

12:32.210 --> 12:34.000
[ Door opens ]
I got it.
I called Jo Wilson.

12:34.000 --> 12:35.290
-Hey.
-She's gonna come --

12:35.290 --> 12:36.380
Hey.
She's here.

12:36.380 --> 12:37.790
Wilson's here. Why?
[ Door closes ]

12:37.790 --> 12:39.250
Dr. Bailey had a cookie.

12:39.250 --> 12:41.880
[ Chuckles ] Oh, crap.
[ Clears throat ]

12:41.880 --> 12:43.250
[ Laughing ]
Why are you laughing?

12:43.250 --> 12:44.670
This is not funny.

12:44.670 --> 12:47.670
This is very not funny.
I'm the chief.

12:47.670 --> 12:49.170
It's very serious.

12:49.170 --> 12:51.120
Will you take the chief
up to the lecture hall, please?

12:51.120 --> 12:52.290
[ Clears throat ]
-Yes. Yes.

12:52.290 --> 12:55.580
I have this,
Dr. Bailey, okay?
Mnh.

12:55.580 --> 12:57.080
You'll do a good job?

12:57.080 --> 12:59.330
'Cause he's very sweet,
and his kids are very scared.

12:59.330 --> 13:02.580
Dr. Bailey.
I have this.

13:02.580 --> 13:03.750
I love you.
Oh, my.

13:03.750 --> 13:05.460
Okay, okay.
Ohh!

13:05.460 --> 13:07.880
-[ Gasps ]
-What?

13:07.880 --> 13:10.040
-Oops.
-Go, go, go.

13:17.170 --> 13:18.500
I don't think they're broken,
but they're too swollen to move.

13:18.500 --> 13:20.170
-This is a bad idea.
-It's the only idea.

13:20.170 --> 13:22.170
He's already open,
and this procedure

13:22.170 --> 13:24.540
takes delicate suturing,
which I cannot do.

13:24.540 --> 13:26.620
But I've never done
a gastrectomy by myself before.

13:26.620 --> 13:28.000
Yeah,
but you've watched a lot.
[ Sighs ]

13:28.000 --> 13:29.380
You can do this.
I believe in you.

13:29.380 --> 13:30.460
Okay, now
you sound stoned.
[ Water running ]

13:30.460 --> 13:32.960
Dr. Grey, patient's BP
is dropping a bit.

13:32.960 --> 13:35.120
Scrub.
[ Doorbell rings ]

13:35.120 --> 13:36.500
[ Knock on door ]
[ Breathes sharply ]

13:36.500 --> 13:37.750
-Hey.
-Calvary's here.

13:37.750 --> 13:38.880
-Oh.
-Is the baby here yet?

13:38.880 --> 13:40.170
Not -- Not yet. What --
What's he doing here?

13:40.170 --> 13:41.540
The baby's not sick,
I hope.

13:41.540 --> 13:44.170
A patient accidentally
brought in pot cookies.

13:44.170 --> 13:45.500
He's high.

13:45.500 --> 13:47.330
So you brought him here?

13:47.330 --> 13:49.170
Well, I wanted to get here
as fast as possible.
[ Owen speaking indistinctly ]

13:49.170 --> 13:50.250
I didn't want you
to freak out.

13:50.250 --> 13:51.540
[ Chuckling ] Oh, yeah.
Bingo.

13:51.540 --> 13:53.250
And I couldn't leave him
alone in my lab

13:53.250 --> 13:54.710
full of very
expensive equipment.

13:54.710 --> 13:56.120
-Huh.
-Are you okay?

13:56.120 --> 13:58.000
-Did you eat a cookie?
-No, no.

13:58.000 --> 13:59.210
I am waiting
for a 6-month-old,

13:59.210 --> 14:01.250
and you bring
a stoned guy to my house?!

14:01.250 --> 14:02.540
We'll just make him
hide in the back

14:02.540 --> 14:03.540
while the social worker's
here.
[ Crunching ]

14:03.540 --> 14:05.120
Listen -- you go shower.

14:05.120 --> 14:06.290
I'm gonna take care
of cleaning the house.

14:06.290 --> 14:08.790
Okay, okay. I can't believe
this is happening.

14:08.790 --> 14:10.580
It is. It's good.

14:10.580 --> 14:12.540
[ Chuckles ]

14:12.540 --> 14:16.040
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, dude.

14:16.040 --> 14:18.750
You're so screwed
right now.

14:18.750 --> 14:21.040
[ Crunching ]

14:23.960 --> 14:24.710
-Hey.
-Hey!

14:24.710 --> 14:25.920
This room is occupied.

14:25.920 --> 14:27.380
-Oops.
-It's okay.

14:27.380 --> 14:29.540
-Sorry, hi. I'm sorry.
-Just -- It's fine.

14:31.380 --> 14:33.040
[ Door closes ]

14:33.040 --> 14:35.670
-What do we do now?
-Huh?

14:35.670 --> 14:37.750
Oh, we just have to wait
for it to pass.

14:37.750 --> 14:40.580
But we can -- I mean, we can
hang out and talk, you know?

14:40.580 --> 14:42.620
Just say whatever
comes into our heads.
Mm.

14:42.620 --> 14:47.750
Just press "play"
and see what comes out.

14:47.750 --> 14:50.290
I really want some cheese.

14:50.290 --> 14:52.880
I pressed fast-forward
on Carina, I think.

14:52.880 --> 14:56.000
It's...such a good food.

14:56.000 --> 14:58.420
[ Sighs ]
There are so many kinds.

14:58.420 --> 15:00.210
I asked her to --
I asked her to stay here

15:00.210 --> 15:01.500
instead of going back
to Italy.

15:01.500 --> 15:02.580
Oh.

15:02.580 --> 15:04.170
Cheddar.

15:04.170 --> 15:06.420
String cheese.

15:06.420 --> 15:07.880
Brie.

15:07.880 --> 15:09.250
The kind with the holes in it.
It's...

15:09.250 --> 15:10.750
You know, we haven't even really
been dating that long.

15:10.750 --> 15:13.040
Swiss!

15:13.040 --> 15:14.830
Oh, I probably
freaked her out.

15:14.830 --> 15:16.460
I mean, who --
who asks a person

15:16.460 --> 15:18.380
to give up their country
for them?

15:18.380 --> 15:21.960
Sometimes I just stand
in the cheese section

15:21.960 --> 15:23.330
of the grocery store
and just...

15:23.330 --> 15:27.580
[ Inhales deeply ]

15:27.580 --> 15:30.540
Mozzarella.

15:30.540 --> 15:33.540
Gouda. Munster.

15:33.540 --> 15:35.040
She'd be a woman
without a country.

15:35.040 --> 15:36.960
Dill Havarti.

15:36.960 --> 15:38.040
[ Screen boops ]

15:38.040 --> 15:39.580
Whoa!

15:39.580 --> 15:40.880
[ Screen boops ]

15:40.880 --> 15:42.000
It goes away.
[ Screen booping ]

15:42.000 --> 15:43.580
Oh, and then it comes back.

15:43.580 --> 15:45.000
[ Chuckles ] Goes away.

15:45.000 --> 15:47.290
-No country.
-Comes back.

15:47.290 --> 15:50.500
[ Laughs ]
It goes away. Comes back.

15:50.500 --> 15:52.250
[ Screen booping ]

15:52.250 --> 15:54.580
♪♪

15:54.580 --> 15:56.880
[ Laughing ]

15:56.880 --> 15:58.920
♪♪

15:58.920 --> 16:00.580
[ Chuckles ]
[ Screen boops ]

16:00.580 --> 16:02.120
♪♪

16:02.120 --> 16:06.460
[ Woman speaking indistinctly
over P.A. ]

16:06.460 --> 16:08.670
[ Sighs ]

16:11.880 --> 16:15.540
What happened?

16:15.540 --> 16:18.250
I heard something I think
I should not have heard.

16:18.250 --> 16:20.420
Also, I've never
done pot before.

16:20.420 --> 16:23.380
Oh, neither have I.
I listen to Mr. T.

16:23.380 --> 16:24.750
Mr. T said...

16:24.750 --> 16:26.620
[ As Mr. T ]
"Kid, don't do drugs."

16:26.620 --> 16:27.710
"Stay in school."

16:27.710 --> 16:29.960
"Treat your mama right."

16:29.960 --> 16:32.500
[ Normal voice ]
I followed Mr. T to a "T."

16:32.500 --> 16:36.080
-[ Laughs ]
-I dared to stay off drugs.

16:36.080 --> 16:38.040
What did you hear?

16:38.040 --> 16:38.920
[ Whispering ]
I don't hear anything.

16:38.920 --> 16:41.170
No. What did you hear?

16:41.170 --> 16:42.420
About what?

16:42.420 --> 16:44.080
You said you heard something
you shouldn't have.

16:44.080 --> 16:45.540
-What did you hear?
-Oh.

16:45.540 --> 16:46.830
Oh, my God!

16:46.830 --> 16:49.080
Oh, it was -- it was bad.

16:49.080 --> 16:51.790
It was really
end-of-an-era bad.

16:51.790 --> 16:53.290
It's the end of an era.

16:56.830 --> 17:00.250
I thought marijuana
made people peaceful,

17:00.250 --> 17:02.500
but I don't think
I ever hated you more.

17:06.420 --> 17:09.120
Jo: Okay, I just divided
the gastrocolic ligament,

17:09.120 --> 17:12.170
and now I'm gonna take down
the short gastric arteries,

17:12.170 --> 17:14.290
which I'll ligate
with 2-0 silks.

17:14.290 --> 17:15.750
Does that sound good?

17:15.750 --> 17:17.830
[ Monitor beeping ]

17:17.830 --> 17:19.540
Okay.

17:19.540 --> 17:21.040
[ Air suctioning ]

17:21.040 --> 17:24.330
-Wait, hang on.
-Hmm.

17:24.330 --> 17:26.710
Bailey said
a total gastrectomy?

17:26.710 --> 17:28.120
Yes. Why?
Well, because

17:28.120 --> 17:29.920
the tumor feels smaller
and more localized

17:29.920 --> 17:31.380
than it did on the scans.

17:31.380 --> 17:32.830
Why wouldn't Bailey want
to save more of his stomach?

17:32.830 --> 17:34.420
I'm not sure.

17:34.420 --> 17:37.750
She doesn't want the guy
to die of cancer -- I know that.

17:37.750 --> 17:39.750
Do you think we can do
a subtotal gastrectomy?

17:39.750 --> 17:40.960
What do you think?

17:40.960 --> 17:42.540
[ Monitor beeping ]

17:42.540 --> 17:44.040
Can I take a look
at the pre-op scans?

17:44.040 --> 17:46.620
I don't have them.

17:46.620 --> 17:47.710
Can I see the scans?

17:47.710 --> 17:50.000
Of course, Doctor.

17:50.000 --> 17:51.670
[ Beeping continues ]

17:51.670 --> 17:54.830
[ Sighs ] Okay.

17:54.830 --> 17:57.830
There's 13 women.
How did I not know that?

17:57.830 --> 17:59.880
I mean [scoffs]
H-How did I -- How --

17:59.880 --> 18:02.210
Why are you so calm?

18:02.210 --> 18:04.580
The cookie might have
something to do with it.

18:06.920 --> 18:08.170
You're messing with me.

18:08.170 --> 18:09.500
-No, I'm not.
-Very funny.

18:09.500 --> 18:10.710
You're messing with me
because I'm a little high.

18:10.710 --> 18:12.040
Or because
you're a little high.

18:12.040 --> 18:13.920
This is not a joke,
Jackson.

18:13.920 --> 18:16.420
This is a secret
you let out of the bag.

18:16.420 --> 18:18.170
How could this even be kept
a secret at all?

18:18.170 --> 18:20.750
Money, honey.
Good God, don't be naive.

18:20.750 --> 18:22.920
A fortune was paid
to silence those women.

18:22.920 --> 18:25.330
No. I understand that,
okay?

18:25.330 --> 18:27.670
I'm saying, "Why?"
Why would anyone protect him?

18:27.670 --> 18:29.040
Why didn't anybody
try to stop him?

18:29.040 --> 18:30.040
Why didn't you
try to stop him?

18:30.040 --> 18:33.250
Because that's
not how it worked.

18:33.250 --> 18:36.500
And...the hope was,
for some, that,

18:36.500 --> 18:38.960
if the financial hit to your
grandfather was great enough,

18:38.960 --> 18:40.920
he would stop the behavior.

18:40.920 --> 18:43.920
And he did.
He did stop.

18:45.540 --> 18:49.120
Oh.

18:49.120 --> 18:50.580
You did this.

18:50.580 --> 18:53.460
♪♪

18:53.460 --> 18:55.580
You covered this up.

18:55.580 --> 18:58.330
♪♪

18:58.330 --> 19:01.420
[ Sighs ]

19:01.420 --> 19:04.540
Oh, Mom.

19:04.540 --> 19:06.920
♪♪

19:06.920 --> 19:09.210
I'm gonna need
child locks and stuff.

19:09.210 --> 19:10.790
Not yet.
Not till they're crawling.

19:10.790 --> 19:12.000
Babies are easy.
[ Crunching ]

19:12.000 --> 19:14.580
You just have to support
their necks like this.

19:14.580 --> 19:15.790
You were supposed to stay
in the bedroom

19:15.790 --> 19:16.920
until after
the social worker leaves.

19:16.920 --> 19:19.580
Smells like Owen in there.

19:19.580 --> 19:22.420
Oh, crap. [ Chuckles ]
I just crushed chip baby.

19:22.420 --> 19:25.380
[ Laughs ]
Get back there.

19:25.380 --> 19:26.380
[ Chip thumps lightly ]

19:26.380 --> 19:29.210
[ Dog barking in distance ]

19:29.210 --> 19:30.830
[ Laughs ] This chip
smells like Owen.

19:30.830 --> 19:32.290
[ Doorbell rings ]

19:32.290 --> 19:33.670
-They're here already.
-Okay.

19:33.670 --> 19:35.000
Take a deep breath.
Didn't think it would
be a baby.

19:35.000 --> 19:36.460
I thought it would be a kid
who I could win over

19:36.460 --> 19:38.420
with, you know,
conversation and ice cream,

19:38.420 --> 19:39.620
but a baby?

19:39.620 --> 19:40.880
-I just --
-Okay, Owen. Look at me.

19:40.880 --> 19:42.670
We're just
gonna take a minute.

19:42.670 --> 19:45.000
I can't think of anyone who is
more prepared for parenthood --

19:45.000 --> 19:46.710
[ Door opens ]
Hi.

19:46.710 --> 19:47.960
Dr. Hunt?

19:47.960 --> 19:51.620
I'm Elaine Hodge, DSHS.

19:51.620 --> 19:53.250
And this is Leo.

19:53.250 --> 19:55.580
No, no.
I'm Dr. Hunt. Owen.

19:55.580 --> 19:57.880
And this is my friend,
Amelia.
[ Leo coos loudly ]

19:57.880 --> 20:00.210
[ Chuckling ] Oh, he's cute.
You got a cute one.

20:00.210 --> 20:01.790
Sometimes,
they look like an old man.

20:01.790 --> 20:03.420
[ Leo crying ]

20:03.420 --> 20:05.500
-Who's this?
-He's just a -- you know --

20:05.500 --> 20:07.000
Dr. Alex Karev.

20:07.000 --> 20:09.460
I'm the Chief of, uh, Pediatric
Surgery at Grey-Sloan.

20:09.460 --> 20:11.620
I came by to give the baby
a quick check-up.

20:11.620 --> 20:15.210
Make sure he doesn't have
signs of jaundice

20:15.210 --> 20:18.000
or RSV
or [crunches] rickets.

20:18.000 --> 20:20.170
That is so nice.
Here you go.

20:20.170 --> 20:21.380
-No.
-No, no. I-I got him.

20:21.380 --> 20:22.830
I got him. I got him.
I got him.

20:22.830 --> 20:24.330
Yeah. Yep, yep, yep.

20:24.330 --> 20:25.500
Hey.

20:25.500 --> 20:29.750
♪♪

20:29.750 --> 20:31.750
Would you like
some chips?

20:31.750 --> 20:34.830
Woman: Engineering to 3 West.
Engineering to 3 West.

20:34.830 --> 20:36.380
Oh, Dr. Qadri.

20:36.380 --> 20:38.040
What happened
to the board?

20:38.040 --> 20:40.000
Dr. Grey
cancelled everything.

20:40.000 --> 20:43.210
It looks like she postponed
the contest, too.

20:43.210 --> 20:44.920
-Why?
-I don't know.

20:44.920 --> 20:48.830
Um, there was
a situation...

20:48.830 --> 20:50.580
with some cookies.

20:50.580 --> 20:52.500
Cook-- Cookies?

20:52.500 --> 20:54.290
[ Monitors beeping rapidly ]

20:54.290 --> 20:56.670
Yes! I'm here.
I'm here first!

20:56.670 --> 20:57.960
Patient's in septic shock.

20:57.960 --> 20:59.330
Systolic's
in the 90s and falling,

20:59.330 --> 21:00.460
heart rate 130s.

21:00.460 --> 21:01.830
He had a bolus of LR,
but...

21:01.830 --> 21:03.670
Oh, man.
He needs a central line.

21:03.670 --> 21:04.880
Then put one in!

21:04.880 --> 21:06.380
I -- You do it.

21:06.380 --> 21:07.750
I can't!
You're the surgeon.

21:07.750 --> 21:09.960
No, I can't.
I'll get someone!

21:09.960 --> 21:12.290
Dr. Roy!
I need help in here!

21:12.290 --> 21:13.580
-Watch out.
-Help!

21:13.580 --> 21:14.500
[ Grunts ]

21:14.500 --> 21:16.830
[ Grunting ]

21:16.830 --> 21:19.830
Oh. Helm, go.
Take him.

21:19.830 --> 21:21.080
Parker, help me with Roy.

21:21.080 --> 21:23.170
My patient
needs a central line!

21:23.170 --> 21:24.960
-I'm on it!
-Casey, get some gloves.

21:24.960 --> 21:26.420
Got it.

21:26.420 --> 21:28.420
Easy, Roy. Easy.

21:36.290 --> 21:37.620
I see why Bailey wanted
to remove the whole stomach.

21:37.620 --> 21:39.420
The tumor is huge. It looks
like it's in the cardia.

21:39.420 --> 21:41.500
I should just follow
standard of care,

21:41.500 --> 21:42.790
a total resection, right?

21:42.790 --> 21:44.170
Why do you keep asking me?

21:44.170 --> 21:45.170
Because you
aren't answering.

21:45.170 --> 21:47.790
What are
the considerations?

21:47.790 --> 21:50.790
Okay, okay,
if I do a total gastrectomy,

21:50.790 --> 21:52.580
it'll make sure
I remove all the cancer,

21:52.580 --> 21:54.040
but he'll eat
through a feeding tube

21:54.040 --> 21:55.960
for the rest of his life.

21:55.960 --> 21:58.460
If I leave
part of the stomach,

21:58.460 --> 22:00.120
then he'll have
a way better quality of life

22:00.120 --> 22:02.250
unless I leave behind
cancer cells,

22:02.250 --> 22:05.500
in which case, he dies
because I kill him.

22:05.500 --> 22:06.790
[ Air suctioning ]

22:06.790 --> 22:08.380
Okay, you know what?
I'm -- I'm doing a total.

22:08.380 --> 22:10.540
-Are you sure?
-Yes. I'm a resident.

22:10.540 --> 22:12.250
I should just follow
the surgery as planned.

22:12.250 --> 22:14.620
You're supposed to do
what's best for the patient.

22:14.620 --> 22:16.540
He's not my patient --
he's Bailey's,

22:16.540 --> 22:17.750
and she handed him off
to you, not me,

22:17.750 --> 22:19.040
so what do I do?

22:19.040 --> 22:20.880
Wilson,
you're a surgeon.

22:20.880 --> 22:23.290
Pull up your big-girl scrubs
and make a call.

22:23.290 --> 22:25.380
-There's a life in your hands.
-I know.

22:25.380 --> 22:26.540
I just wish there was
some way to know

22:26.540 --> 22:28.040
that I was removing
all of the cancer

22:28.040 --> 22:31.040
and not leaving
any behind...

22:31.040 --> 22:33.330
The Pen.
I need the Pen.

22:33.330 --> 22:35.460
I have one in my lab coat.
It's not sterile.

22:35.460 --> 22:38.580
No, no, no.
I need you to find Dr. Webber.

22:38.580 --> 22:40.000
Okay, easy, easy.

22:40.000 --> 22:41.040
Oh, Dr. Webber, I --

22:41.040 --> 22:42.710
Oh, my God!
What happened?!

22:42.710 --> 22:44.330
Okay, it was an accident.
We need to get him to trauma.

22:44.330 --> 22:45.750
What do you need, Schmitt?

22:45.750 --> 22:47.500
I'm supposed to ask to borrow
your -- your Path Pen.

22:47.500 --> 22:49.330
And Dr. Grey and Dr. Wilson
want to know

22:49.330 --> 22:51.420
if it can detect
gastric adenocarcinoma.

22:51.420 --> 22:54.080
It can, and it's in my office,
but I don't want you to go --

22:54.080 --> 22:55.790
-Whoa!
-Whoa.

22:55.790 --> 22:58.040
Okay.
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Okay.

22:58.040 --> 23:00.040
Let's move. Now.

23:00.040 --> 23:01.710
♪♪

23:01.710 --> 23:03.920
[ Screen booping ]

23:03.920 --> 23:07.460
Does it feel right
with Carina?

23:07.460 --> 23:08.750
Boop.

23:08.750 --> 23:10.420
'Cause, you know,
sometimes you can feel scared,

23:10.420 --> 23:11.920
but, then,
you're lying together at night,

23:11.920 --> 23:14.250
and it just feels right.

23:14.250 --> 23:15.880
Yeah.

23:15.880 --> 23:17.620
Yeah, it feels right.

23:17.620 --> 23:21.210
Callie is fun and funny,
and the sex is really great.

23:21.210 --> 23:22.750
-Carina.
-Hm? What?

23:22.750 --> 23:23.880
You said "Callie."

23:23.880 --> 23:25.040
-No, I didn't.
-Yes, you did.

23:25.040 --> 23:26.210
-No, I didn't.
-Yes, you did.

23:26.210 --> 23:27.210
You're high!

23:27.210 --> 23:30.380
Yes, I am,
but you said it.

23:30.380 --> 23:32.210
Press the "rewind" button
on your mind.

23:32.210 --> 23:33.580
[ Screen booping ]

23:33.580 --> 23:36.120
[ Gasps ]
Oh, my God. I did.

23:36.120 --> 23:38.040
Why did I --
Why did I do that?

23:38.040 --> 23:39.500
-Boop.
-They're very different people.

23:39.500 --> 23:40.750
They don't laugh alike.
They don't walk alike.

23:40.750 --> 23:41.920
They definitely
don't talk alike.

23:41.920 --> 23:43.420
-Boop.
-So that's weird.

23:43.420 --> 23:45.750
Boop. [ Chuckles ]
I like that sound.

23:45.750 --> 23:47.250
But both of them
definitely know

23:47.250 --> 23:49.250
how to make me
lose my mind...

23:49.250 --> 23:50.250
in bed.

23:50.250 --> 23:51.420
Hey, where's the liver?

23:51.420 --> 23:52.790
[ Screen beeps slowly ]

23:52.790 --> 23:54.500
-Then...
-I lost the liver!

23:54.500 --> 23:55.960
...Callie just went away.

23:55.960 --> 23:57.880
She took my daughter and
got on a plane, and she left.

23:57.880 --> 23:59.420
What? Um.
Have you seen it?

23:59.420 --> 24:01.540
It's -- It's liver-shaped.

24:01.540 --> 24:03.880
Maybe Eliza Minnick
took a plane, too.

24:03.880 --> 24:06.380
I have no idea because she
ghosted me, so there's that.

24:06.380 --> 24:08.580
Okay, it's red.
[ Breathing quickly ]

24:08.580 --> 24:10.120
It helped
metabolize things,

24:10.120 --> 24:12.250
it eliminated toxins,
and now it's gone!

24:12.250 --> 24:13.960
Eventually,
everyone leaves me.

24:13.960 --> 24:15.420
[ Screen beeps ]
You know?

24:15.420 --> 24:17.420
They got on...
I lost the liver.

24:17.420 --> 24:19.620
...planes or ghostmobiles
or wherever --

24:19.620 --> 24:21.540
they just disappear.

24:21.540 --> 24:24.500
And maybe that's why I held on
so hard to Carina, you know?

24:24.500 --> 24:26.500
Like I was afraid that I was
gonna lose her like I --

24:26.500 --> 24:28.460
like I lose
everybody else.

24:28.460 --> 24:31.040
Maybe I'm just scared
of repeating the past.

24:31.040 --> 24:32.830
-What if she dies?!
-Whoa.

24:32.830 --> 24:34.580
Because I lost the liver!

24:34.580 --> 24:35.710
[ Screen beeping slowly ]

24:35.710 --> 24:39.420
It's not --
It's not good.

24:39.420 --> 24:41.290
I'm not surprised.

24:41.290 --> 24:44.620
I met Harper Avery two times,
and he was awful.

24:44.620 --> 24:46.460
Awful man.

24:46.460 --> 24:49.960
He had a beak like an owl
and a very dry mouth.

24:49.960 --> 24:53.120
I have a very dry mouth.
Do you have that?

24:53.120 --> 24:57.790
Grey has a Harper Avery.
She is part of a family legacy.

24:57.790 --> 25:00.960
Yang was nominated
for one.

25:00.960 --> 25:03.920
She was the best
in our class.

25:03.920 --> 25:06.620
I always wanted
a Harper Avery.

25:06.620 --> 25:08.830
I had a Jackson Avery.

25:08.830 --> 25:10.670
It's not the same thing.
[ Chuckles ]

25:10.670 --> 25:12.170
I have a secret.

25:12.170 --> 25:13.750
I don't even need
this contest,

25:13.750 --> 25:17.750
'cause I just signed a contract
with a manufacturer.

25:17.750 --> 25:19.170
Mm. I'm gonna be rich.

25:19.170 --> 25:21.420
They cannot keep a secret.

25:21.420 --> 25:23.670
I know about Harper.
Mm.

25:23.670 --> 25:25.040
And I know about Maggie.
Mm-hmm.

25:25.040 --> 25:27.040
We're going
to make the TrailBlazer.

25:27.040 --> 25:30.420
Me and
Midnight Pleasures, Inc.

25:30.420 --> 25:32.580
I saw them pull into
the parking lot together.

25:32.580 --> 25:35.170
[ Chuckles ]
They live on opposite
sides of town.

25:35.170 --> 25:37.670
There's only one reason
that they would carpool.

25:37.670 --> 25:39.420
My husband said,
"You really want to go

25:39.420 --> 25:41.330
into business
with a sex-toy company?"

25:41.330 --> 25:44.540
But I have a secret,
too.

25:44.540 --> 25:46.000
I've been seeing someone.

25:46.000 --> 25:49.120
I said to him,
"I have a colonoscopy device.

25:49.120 --> 25:51.460
It goes
into people's rectums.

25:51.460 --> 25:55.670
This company already has items
that function similarly.

25:55.670 --> 25:58.790
Don't make it nasty."

25:58.790 --> 26:01.330
Wait. What?

26:01.330 --> 26:03.830
You're making
your colonoscopy TrailBlazer

26:03.830 --> 26:05.500
with a sex-toy company?

26:05.500 --> 26:08.080
Meredith Grey called it
the "TAILBlazer."

26:08.080 --> 26:09.790
That's where
I got the idea.

26:09.790 --> 26:11.960
[ Chuckles ]

26:11.960 --> 26:15.210
[ Chuckles softly ]

26:15.210 --> 26:17.420
[ Laughs ]

26:17.420 --> 26:18.790
[ Snorts ]

26:18.790 --> 26:20.120
[ Wheels rolling ]

26:20.120 --> 26:21.210
[ Telephone ringing ]

26:21.210 --> 26:23.880
[ Indistinct conversations ]

26:23.880 --> 26:26.330
Dr. Schmitt?
Is it over?

26:26.330 --> 26:27.750
Dr. Bailey said
it wouldn't take this long.

26:27.750 --> 26:28.790
Is he okay?

26:28.790 --> 26:30.460
He's not out yet.

26:30.460 --> 26:32.540
I had to get some equipment
so we can finish.

26:32.540 --> 26:33.670
Oh, my God.
What is that?

26:33.670 --> 26:35.750
[ Gasps ] Something
went wrong, didn't it?

26:35.750 --> 26:37.290
Something unexpected?

26:37.290 --> 26:39.380
Is my dad gonna die?

26:39.380 --> 26:41.080
Please don't let him die,
Dr. Schmitt.

26:41.080 --> 26:43.750
No. No.
There's no complication.

26:43.750 --> 26:48.000
And I will do everything I can
to make sure he's all right.

26:48.000 --> 26:50.290
In fact, I'm gonna
do that right now.

26:50.290 --> 26:51.880
[ Ringing,
conversations continue ]

26:51.880 --> 26:55.040
[ Wheels rolling ]

26:57.210 --> 26:59.000
What was I thinking?

26:59.000 --> 27:00.830
You can tell, right, that I
don't know what I'm doing?
[ Leo shouting ]

27:00.830 --> 27:02.380
Alex: [ High-pitched voice ]
"Yes, I hate you already.

27:02.380 --> 27:03.620
You're the worst."

27:03.620 --> 27:05.080
Alex, stop it.

27:05.080 --> 27:06.830
"No, you're making me
high-strung and competitive

27:06.830 --> 27:08.250
as we speak!"

27:08.250 --> 27:10.290
You are not helping.
No, no. He's right.

27:10.290 --> 27:12.290
They say all those kids tend
to have type-A personalities

27:12.290 --> 27:14.580
'cause their parents
are so stressed

27:14.580 --> 27:15.920
about every little thing,

27:15.920 --> 27:17.120
and then,
second baby comes along

27:17.120 --> 27:19.120
and they're
more comfortable,

27:19.120 --> 27:20.540
so that kid gets to be
more easygoing.

27:20.540 --> 27:22.420
[ Crying ]
You just explained
so much.

27:22.420 --> 27:25.210
Yeah, I always thought Megan
was lucky that way.

27:25.210 --> 27:27.000
I was thinking about me being
the youngest of five.

27:27.000 --> 27:29.500
"Am I getting a little sister?
When's she coming?"
[ Coos ]

27:29.500 --> 27:32.330
Alex.

27:32.330 --> 27:34.460
Wait. This isn't the way
to the store.

27:34.460 --> 27:37.330
Nope. This group is not ready
to be seen in public,

27:37.330 --> 27:38.830
but I know where to get
everything you need

27:38.830 --> 27:40.750
because my sister-in-law
is a pack rat.

27:40.750 --> 27:43.040
"Daddy,
can I have a pony?"

27:43.040 --> 27:45.500
[ Leo crying ]

27:45.500 --> 27:46.540
Shh, shh.

27:46.540 --> 27:48.960
[ Crying continues ]

27:49.790 --> 27:52.250
[ Breathes heavily ]
It really works?

27:52.250 --> 27:55.170
Well, it's supposed to.
It's still in the testing stage.

27:55.170 --> 27:57.290
We're testing it?
On this guy?

27:57.290 --> 27:59.080
He -- He's got a wife
and two kids.

27:59.080 --> 28:00.330
They're very nice,

28:00.330 --> 28:02.420
and they really, really
want him to stay alive.

28:02.420 --> 28:04.120
And I promised them
I'd make sure he gets

28:04.120 --> 28:05.750
the best possible care.
[ Sighs ]

28:05.750 --> 28:06.750
So, maybe, Dr. Grey,

28:06.750 --> 28:07.790
if you could
just tell Dr. Wilson --

28:07.790 --> 28:10.040
Schmitt, be quiet.
She's got it.

28:10.040 --> 28:12.500
Hey, look.
The distal end...

28:12.500 --> 28:14.920
[ Buzzer ]
Adenocarcinoma.

28:14.920 --> 28:18.460
But if I go one centimeter
proximally...
[ Chimes ]

28:18.460 --> 28:20.580
-[ Breathes sharply ] It works.
-[ Laughs ]

28:20.580 --> 28:21.960
[ Chuckling ]
It's working.

28:21.960 --> 28:23.380
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, my God.

28:25.120 --> 28:27.120
I'm gonna save
half his stomach.

28:29.250 --> 28:30.580
Linear stapler.

28:30.580 --> 28:36.290
♪♪

28:40.620 --> 28:44.500
Time of death -- 16:06.

28:44.500 --> 28:46.620
Acute liver...
[breathes deeply]

28:46.620 --> 28:49.580
...disappearance.

28:49.580 --> 28:53.290
We did everything we could,
but we could not save her.

28:53.290 --> 28:56.000
Our thoughts and prayers
are with her,

28:56.000 --> 28:59.790
her family,
and her friends.

28:59.790 --> 29:03.120
♪♪

29:03.120 --> 29:05.420
[ Gasping ]

29:05.420 --> 29:08.920
♪♪

29:08.920 --> 29:11.540
[ Crying ]

29:11.540 --> 29:15.040
♪♪

29:22.250 --> 29:24.290
Good. Now you'll want
to ligate the branch.

29:24.290 --> 29:26.460
Why are you
letting them do this?

29:26.460 --> 29:27.710
Because they need
to practice.

29:27.710 --> 29:29.080
Does it have to be on me?

29:29.080 --> 29:30.790
Roy, I'm gonna give you
a light sedation.

29:30.790 --> 29:32.380
Thank you.

29:32.380 --> 29:35.000
Mm.

29:35.000 --> 29:36.580
[ Clatters lightly ]

29:36.580 --> 29:38.620
Wait. Wait.

29:38.620 --> 29:40.710
Is that diazepam?

29:40.710 --> 29:43.290
Does that interact with...
other drugs?

29:43.290 --> 29:47.250
♪♪

29:47.250 --> 29:49.040
Okay, we fed you.
We changed you.

29:49.040 --> 29:50.540
Everything's okay.
[ Leo cries ]

29:50.540 --> 29:53.170
This is a very, very,
very long scarf.

29:53.170 --> 29:54.620
That's a Moby.

29:54.620 --> 29:56.960
You wrap it around yourself and
the baby so you can carry him.

29:56.960 --> 29:58.380
Okay, calm down.
Calm down, Leo.

29:58.380 --> 30:00.710
It's okay. It's okay.

30:00.710 --> 30:01.790
Do you want
a diaper genie?

30:01.790 --> 30:03.620
Does he come
to the house?

30:03.620 --> 30:05.120
Uh, I guess so.

30:05.120 --> 30:06.460
How do you know
what all this stuff is?

30:06.460 --> 30:07.830
You'll figure it out.

30:07.830 --> 30:10.120
Okay, I got you.
I got you. Shh, shh, shh.

30:10.120 --> 30:13.330
[ Sighs ] Amelia?
[ Cooing softly ]

30:13.330 --> 30:14.420
Was this a bad idea?

30:14.420 --> 30:17.500
What? No.
You've wanted this forever.

30:17.500 --> 30:19.710
Yeah, I know what I wanted,
but what about him?

30:19.710 --> 30:22.290
You know, who's to say
I was supposed to be a father?

30:22.290 --> 30:23.500
Maybe this was all going
how it was supposed to,

30:23.500 --> 30:24.670
and I just forced it.

30:24.670 --> 30:26.420
Owen, what you're
doing is beautiful.

30:26.420 --> 30:27.540
You're fostering him.

30:27.540 --> 30:29.000
You're --
You're being there for him

30:29.000 --> 30:30.250
when nobody else is.

30:30.250 --> 30:32.120
Ha!
My foster parents sucked.

30:32.120 --> 30:33.580
-Alex!
-No, for real.

30:33.580 --> 30:35.880
They just stuck me in a room
with some other kids

30:35.880 --> 30:38.290
and then collected
a check.

30:38.290 --> 30:40.080
Except for one.
There was one guy.

30:40.080 --> 30:42.380
He worked nights
in a warehouse.

30:42.380 --> 30:44.120
Come home, dead tired
at the crack of dawn,

30:44.120 --> 30:46.040
and go straight to bed.

30:46.040 --> 30:48.750
But then, an hour later,
he'd wake up,

30:48.750 --> 30:50.170
just so
he could eat cereal with me

30:50.170 --> 30:53.540
and tell me, you know,
"Have a good day,"

30:53.540 --> 30:54.670
before I went to school.

30:54.670 --> 30:56.710
Then he'd
go back to sleep.

30:56.710 --> 31:02.210
Wasn't much, but, you know,
he just gave a crap, you know?

31:02.210 --> 31:05.750
He gave a crap,
and you, my friend,

31:05.750 --> 31:08.420
you are giving [Chuckling]
so many craps right now.

31:08.420 --> 31:10.620
[ Leo cooing ]
This man's got it made.

31:10.620 --> 31:11.960
He's not crying.

31:11.960 --> 31:14.330
Look. I did it.

31:14.330 --> 31:15.580
[ Thuds softly ]

31:15.580 --> 31:17.210
Mnh. Maybe not.

31:17.210 --> 31:18.960
[ Cooing ]

31:18.960 --> 31:21.120
♪♪

31:21.120 --> 31:23.580
It was a very
different time then.

31:23.580 --> 31:25.420
It was his name.
It was his foundation.

31:25.420 --> 31:26.540
He made the rules.

31:26.540 --> 31:28.080
Oh, please
stop talking, Mom.

31:28.080 --> 31:29.540
I'm just trying
to help you understand.

31:29.540 --> 31:31.290
Well, I wish
you would help those women.

31:31.290 --> 31:32.580
Look at me.

31:32.580 --> 31:34.620
You told me to step up.

31:34.620 --> 31:36.960
You wanted to buy this hospital,
I wanted nothing to do with it,

31:36.960 --> 31:39.000
and you said,
"Step up. Take the lead.

31:39.000 --> 31:40.620
Take part in what
this family has built," right?

31:40.620 --> 31:42.330
And you did.
You didn't tell me
what the hell it was built on.

31:42.330 --> 31:44.790
No, no.
You do not get to do that.

31:44.790 --> 31:48.120
You do not get to stand there
in judgment of me.
That --

31:48.120 --> 31:49.830
30 years ago,
getting harassed at work,

31:49.830 --> 31:52.580
getting groped at work wasn't
something we could protest.

31:52.580 --> 31:55.080
It was something we had to take
with our morning coffee.

31:55.080 --> 31:56.620
It was part of the job.

31:56.620 --> 31:58.380
and if we made a noise,
if we fussed,

31:58.380 --> 32:00.880
we were told
we were overreacting

32:00.880 --> 32:02.500
and, more often than not,
we lost the job

32:02.500 --> 32:05.330
and our reputation
along with it.

32:05.330 --> 32:08.380
I was not then
who I am now.

32:08.380 --> 32:11.000
I didn't have the voice then
that I have now.

32:11.000 --> 32:12.420
I had choices.

32:12.420 --> 32:14.420
I could stand there
and let your grandfather

32:14.420 --> 32:16.920
fire those women
and drag them through the mud,

32:16.920 --> 32:21.080
or I could make sure
they got some money,

32:21.080 --> 32:24.670
a leg to stand on,
a path to move forward on.

32:26.670 --> 32:30.710
I'm not ashamed of myself,
Jackson,

32:30.710 --> 32:34.210
but I am ashamed
of what your grandfather did.

32:34.210 --> 32:35.790
And I'm so sorry that now

32:35.790 --> 32:39.460
you have to carry that burden
along with me.

32:39.460 --> 32:42.670
And I'm sorry that that burden
might just bring this family,

32:42.670 --> 32:44.170
this entire hospital,

32:44.170 --> 32:47.540
and all of his hospitals
down.

32:48.960 --> 32:50.120
[ Sighs ]

32:50.120 --> 32:52.080
[ Monitor beeping ]

32:52.080 --> 32:53.880
Okay. That's it.

32:53.880 --> 32:55.170
Now what?

32:55.170 --> 32:56.290
Well, now
we cross our fingers

32:56.290 --> 32:57.830
and pray we made
the right decision.

32:57.830 --> 32:58.920
[ Air suctioning ]

32:58.920 --> 33:01.460
You did.

33:01.460 --> 33:04.880
You did exactly what I would
have done, except for The Pen.

33:04.880 --> 33:07.670
I wouldn't
have needed that.

33:07.670 --> 33:10.170
You could have saved me a lot
of stress if you told me sooner.

33:10.170 --> 33:11.540
Well,
that's not how you learn.

33:11.540 --> 33:13.460
I'm pretty sure
having an experienced surgeon

33:13.460 --> 33:15.580
tell you what to do
is exactly how you learn.

33:15.580 --> 33:17.120
You know
exactly what to do.

33:17.120 --> 33:19.210
You're a highly
competent surgeon.

33:19.210 --> 33:21.580
You've memorized
and practiced every move,

33:21.580 --> 33:24.040
but making tough choices
under immense pressure --

33:24.040 --> 33:26.830
that's how you become
a truly great surgeon.

33:26.830 --> 33:29.500
[ Monitor beeping ]

33:29.500 --> 33:31.580
And now you get
to go tell his family that,

33:31.580 --> 33:33.580
not only did you save
his life,

33:33.580 --> 33:35.460
you saved
his quality of life.

33:35.460 --> 33:37.120
♪♪

33:37.120 --> 33:39.420
I'm gonna go check
on our stoners.

33:39.420 --> 33:40.790
[ Monitor beeping ]

33:40.790 --> 33:43.580
Nice work.

33:43.580 --> 33:45.670
[ Door closes ]

33:45.670 --> 33:49.120
[ Both vocalizing to the tune of
"Scotland the Brave" ]

33:51.500 --> 33:54.120
[ Vocalizing continues ]

33:56.250 --> 33:59.080
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:00.420 --> 34:01.540
What's happening?

34:01.540 --> 34:03.040
We're having a funeral.

34:03.040 --> 34:05.080
Whose?
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:05.080 --> 34:06.830
Mm, Harper Avery.
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:06.830 --> 34:09.420
The Harper Averies.
The end of an era.

34:09.420 --> 34:10.670
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:10.670 --> 34:12.420
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:12.420 --> 34:13.960
What are you talking
about?

34:13.960 --> 34:19.120
[ Vocalizing continues ]

34:19.120 --> 34:20.540
[ Vocalizing stops ]

34:21.620 --> 34:22.830
[ Swallows deeply ]

34:22.830 --> 34:24.040
[ Siren wails in distance,
horns honking ]

34:24.040 --> 34:25.580
[ Indistinct conversations ]

34:25.580 --> 34:27.290
You were put into
a terrible position, Mom,

34:27.290 --> 34:29.120
and I doubted you.

34:29.120 --> 34:30.670
I forgot who you were
for a moment. I'm sorry.

34:30.670 --> 34:32.460
It's all right, baby.

34:32.460 --> 34:33.880
I don't know
what's gonna happen next,

34:33.880 --> 34:35.580
but it's not
gonna be good.

34:35.580 --> 34:36.750
Well, we just got
to tell the truth

34:36.750 --> 34:38.080
and get out ahead
of this thing.

34:38.080 --> 34:41.120
We'll get in touch with those
women and make this right.

34:41.120 --> 34:43.830
Yeah. Yeah.
[ Door opens ]

34:43.830 --> 34:45.670
Tell me it isn't true.

34:45.670 --> 34:48.040
[ Sighs ]

34:48.040 --> 34:51.920
I've spent my whole life
working for that award.

34:51.920 --> 34:53.620
What did Harper Avery do?

34:53.620 --> 34:56.750
♪♪

34:56.750 --> 35:00.670
Well, I guess
we might as well start now.

35:00.670 --> 35:02.170
Mm-hmm.

35:02.170 --> 35:03.960
We're gonna start with you,
Meredith.

35:11.330 --> 35:12.460
[ Sirens wailing in distance ]

35:12.460 --> 35:14.120
So, was my mother
one of these women?

35:14.120 --> 35:16.290
No. No, your mother
was not one of the women.

35:16.290 --> 35:18.170
So, these women --
they were offered money

35:18.170 --> 35:20.040
in exchange
for what exactly?

35:20.040 --> 35:22.580
In exchange for silence
and an agreement

35:22.580 --> 35:24.420
that they would never
work at a Harper Avery hospital

35:24.420 --> 35:26.750
or enter
the Harper Avery Awards.

35:26.750 --> 35:29.120
I mean,
my mother spent her career

35:29.120 --> 35:31.830
trying to win
Harper Avery Awards.

35:31.830 --> 35:33.710
She lost
her best friend over it.

35:33.710 --> 35:37.960
His initials take up
half the space in her journals.

35:37.960 --> 35:40.880
Oh, my God.

35:40.880 --> 35:43.170
Does the name Marie Cerone
mean anything to you?

35:43.170 --> 35:46.500
Yes.
She was one of the women.

35:46.500 --> 35:49.540
So my mother had to take
her name off of the paper

35:49.540 --> 35:52.580
or she would never be able
to win a Harper Avery.

35:56.750 --> 35:59.250
Son of a bitch.

35:59.250 --> 36:01.380
Will I be able
to do surgery again?

36:01.380 --> 36:05.290
No. Your tox screen
came back positive.

36:05.290 --> 36:07.290
This morning, you were asked
if you had eaten a cookie,

36:07.290 --> 36:08.500
and you said, "No."

36:08.500 --> 36:09.960
Half the attendings
ate those cookies!

36:09.960 --> 36:11.580
And acted responsibly.

36:11.580 --> 36:13.330
You lied so you could get
another surgery.

36:13.330 --> 36:15.000
You put patients at risk.

36:15.000 --> 36:17.500
So...I-I'm suspended?

36:17.500 --> 36:19.040
No.

36:19.040 --> 36:21.040
You're fired.

36:21.040 --> 36:22.960
[ Tablet scrapes lightly ]

36:22.960 --> 36:24.750
Meredith:
Surgeons can benefit

36:24.750 --> 36:27.500
from altered states
of consciousness...
[ Door closes ]

36:27.500 --> 36:28.790
...but only when
they're achieved naturally.

36:28.790 --> 36:30.210
Anchorwoman: The women allege
that Dr. Harper Avery

36:30.210 --> 36:32.170
made unwanted advances

36:32.170 --> 36:34.500
and then barred them
from working at any hospital

36:34.500 --> 36:36.830
that received funding
from his foundation,

36:36.830 --> 36:39.540
effectively crippling
their medical careers.

36:39.540 --> 36:42.500
Today, they say they're
finished being silenced.

36:42.500 --> 36:44.330
Meredith: The lows drive us
to do better.

36:44.330 --> 36:46.960
[ Sighs ] Well,
we're not out ahead of it.

36:46.960 --> 36:52.380
♪♪

36:52.380 --> 36:55.380
[ Bag zipping ]

36:55.380 --> 36:57.120
Hey.

36:57.120 --> 36:59.290
I heard
about the cookies.

36:59.290 --> 37:01.000
[ Door closes ]
Do you need a ride home?

37:01.000 --> 37:02.500
You're still here.

37:02.500 --> 37:05.250
Of course. I wouldn't leave
without saying goodbye.

37:05.250 --> 37:08.460
The highs of saving a life are
the reward for a job well done.

37:08.460 --> 37:11.540
♪ You and me will be always ♪

37:11.540 --> 37:17.380
♪ I'll be honest,
there's a lot I don't know ♪

37:17.380 --> 37:21.120
♪ So much of this
is out of our control ♪

37:21.120 --> 37:23.120
Amelia:
Here's his jacket and bag,

37:23.120 --> 37:25.540
and I packed him snacks
for the road.

37:25.540 --> 37:27.080
-Thanks.
-You look happy.

37:27.080 --> 37:28.250
I had a really,
really good day.

37:28.250 --> 37:29.830
♪ 'Cause there's
a short, short list ♪

37:29.830 --> 37:31.540
♪ Of people
in it for the long haul ♪

37:31.540 --> 37:33.540
[ Door opens ]

37:33.540 --> 37:36.580
And then there are times when
our state of mind is altered,

37:36.580 --> 37:39.960
and it has nothing to do
with brain chemistry.

37:39.960 --> 37:41.880
Owen: [ Sighs ]

37:41.880 --> 37:43.540
-He's finally down?
-Yeah.

37:43.540 --> 37:45.790
I think I was down to 35 bottles
of beer on the wall.

37:45.790 --> 37:47.540
I heard.
[ Chuckles ]

37:47.540 --> 37:50.290
Ohh. [ Groans ]
I've had him less than 24 hours,

37:50.290 --> 37:52.250
and I expose him to drugs
and heavy drinking.

37:52.250 --> 37:54.620
I'm corrupting a baby.
[ Sighs ]

37:54.620 --> 37:56.040
You still worried
about screwing him up?

37:56.040 --> 37:57.880
No, I moved on to worrying

37:57.880 --> 38:00.960
about SIDS and...rickets,
yeah.

38:00.960 --> 38:03.080
Well, you're supposed
to worry about that.
[ Chuckles ]

38:03.080 --> 38:05.120
If you weren't worried
about that, I would be worried.

38:05.120 --> 38:06.540
Mm-hmm.

38:06.540 --> 38:07.920
You're gonna be fine.
Yeah.

38:07.920 --> 38:09.330
You should go get some sleep
while he sleeps.

38:09.330 --> 38:11.620
Mm. I'm just gonna
sleep here.
Mm.

38:11.620 --> 38:14.540
[ Leo crying ]

38:14.540 --> 38:16.080
Mm.

38:16.080 --> 38:18.120
Okay.
Thank you for coming.

38:18.120 --> 38:19.500
[ Groans ]

38:19.500 --> 38:20.830
Okay.

38:20.830 --> 38:23.210
♪ That nothing in this world
can change ♪

38:23.210 --> 38:25.080
♪ Hey ♪

38:25.080 --> 38:28.500
♪ You and me will be always ♪

38:28.500 --> 38:30.960
♪ Always ♪
[ Leo cooing ]

38:30.960 --> 38:33.120
♪ You and me
will be always ♪

38:33.120 --> 38:35.120
What are you...?
You staying?

38:35.120 --> 38:37.120
Yeah,
I figure for one night.

38:37.120 --> 38:39.790
Thank God.
I mean, uh, thank you.

38:39.790 --> 38:42.580
She's staying. Yeah.

38:42.580 --> 38:43.790
[ Cooing loudly ]

38:43.790 --> 38:45.580
-Ooh. Hey.
-Hi, baby.

38:45.580 --> 38:48.290
Why are you wide awake?
Why are you still awake?
Yes. Yeah.

38:48.290 --> 38:49.620
It's time for sleep,
little Leo.

38:49.620 --> 38:51.710
There you go.
There you go.

38:51.710 --> 38:55.380
New opportunities open us up
to greater possibilities.

38:55.380 --> 38:57.380
♪ I'm gonna be your always
always ♪

38:57.380 --> 38:58.420
♪ Hey ♪

38:58.420 --> 38:59.460
[ Gulping ]

38:59.460 --> 39:03.080
♪ You and me will be always ♪

39:03.080 --> 39:06.460
♪ Now, see, your clothes, your
shoes, and your best friends ♪

39:06.460 --> 39:07.460
♪ They ain't
gonna stay the same ♪

39:07.460 --> 39:09.500
-[ Sighs ]
-All right. Come on.

39:09.500 --> 39:12.380
Harper Avery.
I can't believe it.

39:12.380 --> 39:13.790
I know.

39:13.790 --> 39:14.960
Did Jackson know?

39:14.960 --> 39:16.880
Not until today.

39:16.880 --> 39:18.420
♪ The one thing that nothing
in this world can change ♪

39:18.420 --> 39:19.670
What are you gonna do?

39:19.670 --> 39:20.750
I don't know.

39:20.750 --> 39:22.120
♪ Hey ♪

39:22.120 --> 39:25.710
♪ You and me will be always ♪

39:25.710 --> 39:28.210
♪ Always, yeah ♪

39:28.210 --> 39:31.290
♪ You and me will be always ♪

39:31.290 --> 39:33.620
New information
and a new perspective

39:33.620 --> 39:37.290
can permanently
shift our consciousness.

39:37.290 --> 39:40.580
And the way we see the world
will never be the same.

39:40.580 --> 39:43.210
♪♪

39:55.880 --> 40:04.040
♪♪

40:04.040 --> 40:12.170
♪♪

40:12.170 --> 40:20.920
♪♪
